  "text": "CORRESPONDENCE 15 October 2024 Zoie T. Diana University of Toronto, Toronto, Canada. Chelsea M. Rochman University of Toronto, Toronto, Canada. Nicholas Mallos Ocean Conservancy, Washington DC, USA. Final negotiations for the first-ever United Nations treaty on plastic pollution are due to take place at the end of November. The latest treaty draft states two major objectives: to end plastic pollution and to protect human and environmental health. This will not be possible without tackling microplastic pollution — particularly secondary microplastics produced by the breakdown of larger items, such as textiles, tyres and paints. Access options Access Nature and 54 other Nature Portfolio journalsGet Nature+, our best-value online-access subscription$29.99 / 30 dayscancel any timeSubscribe to this journalReceive 51 print issues and online access$199.00 per yearonly $3.90 per issueRent or buy this articlePrices vary by article typefrom$1.95to$39.95Prices may be subject to local taxes which are calculated during checkout Additional access options: Log in Learn about institutional subscriptions Read our FAQs Contact customer support Nature 634, 545 (2024) doi: https://doi.org/10.1038/d41586-024-03360-y Competing Interests The authors declare no competing interests. Related Articles UN plastics treaty: don’t let lobbyists drown out researchers We must protect the global plastics treaty from corporate interference Three ways to solve the plastics pollution crisis Plastic pollution: Three problems that a global treaty could solve See more letters to the editor Subjects Latest on:",
